The first virtual operator is already going to reach the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is well developed and our operators offer almost all services like their Western European partners.
However, here we are still missing something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not gonna take long to get here.
That Czech operators are part of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it in mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming fees, a paradoxical situation is likely to be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they are sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high as compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTU), Pavel Dvořák, also said that there is no place for any other operator in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in prices to which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was demonstrated that there is a place for such operators and that they can be successful.
In addition, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighbouring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking there is the Penta group, which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U: fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order to be able to function effectively, it is enough for many less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages that, however, often counter the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers at least half of the cheap in relation to competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good blow to a trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically directed at man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - it is the operator who likes and who can be trusted," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could be hooked up in our country.
Vodafone's spokesman, Miroslav Čepický, doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services it is relatively saturated. "
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there are any virtual operators in the Czech Republic, that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region, "said in telephone conversation for mobil.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, he said that the current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do their best to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest on the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile services.
And the sooner the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings, "said the group's spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they show better times.
It seems that, for unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"We now believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date, no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this field, "said Vhímil Sršeț, spokesman for Telefónica O2, for mobil.cz.
Other operators are concerned about the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional conformity with O2's opinion, adds: "We have not yet registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
He adds: "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some specific contract that would be possible to study on such a short horizon. "
Vodafone focuses rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
We regard this as the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field is in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile. "
Responsible offices - with the operators nail and meat
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition, leading to a fall in prices and thus to a fall in profits.
Then why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of that is the grip when U: fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTU was at the time of the entry of U: fon by the T-Mobile society.
It is attested by public information available on the ČTU websites.
But precisely now U: fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile phone market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
As regards the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would be for him and, above all, for his services great requirements. "
This is why this access to mobile operators is extremely disheartening because of the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licensing (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator is concluded.
To date no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential stakeholders rather was not interesting enough for the classic operators, "he added to our question Kristián Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of External Relations.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than just a consideration, apart from that, they must note that no one takes advantage of their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the foreign country where virtual operators operate normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile phone services"
Of course, pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and price reductions do not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
The dramatic shock in this whole case really lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of petrol at the gas stations, for it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, lack, as well as telecommunications regulators, "he added to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is of course an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTU according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of his network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise in a similar way.
The current complaints from the parties concerned (the GTS Novera company is inluded) show that in all negotiations with the operators they are confronted with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility in the ČTU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the UOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the extension of the competence of ČTU in the field of commercial tenders was recently submitted and did not take effect, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This must be well known to the representatives of UOHS, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks.
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator that already exists in Czech mobile networks is unnoticed.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile services, but only a part are public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same by ordering a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions on all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If such cases were to be discovered as the ones he cites, it could be said of an infringement in the terms of the contract that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," he replied to the question about this problem, Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
In the case of the three companies mentioned above, this can be the case of thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a profit that is not negligible and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows for such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that your phone's SIM card is not in your name so you cannot dispose absolutely of it as a normal customer of the operators. "
This is precisely what the ČTU should find to be minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the UOHS.
If mobile phone operators are entangled in this type of procedure, why block the virtual operator's entry?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not going to want to be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this history and that its commercial conditions do not allow it.
When we'll stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant fall in service prices.
At the same time, in virtually all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this eruption.
The arguments used by these were almost all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with quality of service, etc.
In the more advanced countries, however, the regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to get the first virtual operator to emerge, and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Authority is passing this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases will convince them.
But let's not despair.
If this backstage information is correct and the virtual operator really gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators let any virtual mobile phone operator in, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we will perhaps stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new hymn was recorded by the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with male voice and one with female voice, one with Chorus and another instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka are responsible for the song.
The authors of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can hear all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this national Czech song to be one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio has already said before that it intentionally chose for the Solos singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with the two and then, also, with the Choir, to look at the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be consistent," he said.
The official Czech anthem celebrates next year its 175 anniversary.
The song Where, my Home first sounded in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetan Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
He won popularity and people made it his own.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
