The MHD in Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic bonus in their pockets instead of a paper ticket is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company.
This can now be acquired by almost 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual bonus (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the infocentres and posts of the transport company at the Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Homešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka stations.
The bonds can be purchased on the Internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than 400 people.
Those who start using the Internet as a form of trade can definitely begin to forget about ticket outlets at metro stations, where they had to line up regularly so far to take out a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased on the Internet, and the Opencard card is recharged to you in one of the 13 subsidiaries of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is a window available to passengers with prepared staff that helps those interested with the purchase on the Internet and also with the recharge of the bonus purchased on their card," said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus in the Opencard on the automatic vending machines that are found in some of the vestibules of the subway.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket-chopping machine and the travelers will probably have already fixed on them at the stations of the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská subway.
"Now there are five in the city, but by the end of the year there would have to be eighty," Opatrný concluded.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid bonus will be loaded only on it.
The electronic bonds since tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, on the bypass trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 used mainly by the inhabitants of the central Bohemia localities.
"In the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the area of the bonus," explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drapual of the organization Ropid that sets the times of the collective transport of Prague.
The bypass buses have their reading cards mounted at the driver's locker.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany it with the Opencard in the place intended for it on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonds, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," he added.
Passengers who do not travel on the bypass buses and do not remember when they are finished with the validity of the bonus can go to vending machines where the cards are recharged.
