I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or someone else being able to prove it so far, although we can't even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case at least we can expect it because all human brains present the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we dedicate ourselves to other species and include the questions about the feeling and in general about the consciousness, we enter the unknown sphere because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as the other animals: it does the dead, runs away or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists draw conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Of course I don't think so.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to spread our subjective experience to that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated with human consciousness of the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their participation in short memory and executive functions that lead conduct).
This broad part is much more developed in the case of people than other primates and seems to be absolutely missing in other creatures.
