Repeated alcohol drivers must install the 'alapocouk'
Interior wants the driver with three administrative penalties for alcoholemia, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting drunk, or if it does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and is now included in the annual report of the State Prosecutor's Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last for a period of one year.
The purpose is to reintegrate the driver, so the driver will also receive a road re-education course.
In addition to the Fiscalia General de Segurida Vial, the General Directorate of Traffic (DGT) and the Fundación Instituto Tecnológico para la Seguridad del Auto (FITSA) will participate in the experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of the motorists reported more than once for driving drunk again take the car.
The alapocock would avoid this because it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the alcohol rate in the air that is spirated and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not blow abtes; or when an alcohol concentration is detected, it is higher than that allowed.
The cost is higher than EUR 1,000 and would be borne by the person concerned.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices reduce violations by up to 65% during the first year of implementation.
And in Spain it is estimated that 115 people could save their lives every year.
The measure is subject to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address such behaviour before it results in criminal offences.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means, and yet the necessary reform by criminal means requires a reform in an organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial mode, although it has already been piloted in some public service and industrial vehicles.
Just tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow for an initiative of the PSOE in which it intends to install this system on school buses, just as it has been carried out in France.
