Talk asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I'm not talking about those who wake up very skewed by telling us something that happened the day before, but about children who speak when they are asleep.
The first time it happens, you might get scared, but it really doesn't matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somnilokia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one of them was told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadic (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more regularly (every day, once a week, once in meseS...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause to determine its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep changes such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (peeing) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be so.
As mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overarousal.
It's a little unstudied, anyway.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be useful to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to see if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to get the child too excited before you go to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who are hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain internal calm.
This will encourage the child to have a quieter dream.
Once the somniloquies appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day you will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his dream.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes you should consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), do not fall into the temptation to ask him an interrogation to get information.
You will get nothing, because when you are asleep you are not aware to organize your thought.
You will also hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming of to say that, with which you will be very careful how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child you can question him at night to know his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts just a few minutes.
