The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has again been one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, he reconquered the public's confidence that had been seriously emptied by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and the discontent of the public, the Canadian government conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Kover, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to ensure that such a disaster did not occur any more.
While Judge Kover was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gelineau committee carried out this mission.
As a result of Gelineau and Kover's reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all the other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, he recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
After having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence, "he said before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebequese population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is an extremely fragile thing."
Since its creation, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were attending in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of crazy cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we support one of the main recommendations of Kover and Gelineau's reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we put in place exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown out of all doubt that this disease is transmitted by the blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied had meaning. "
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleide acid tests that allow direct detection of the presence of the virus and not of antibodies to the virus in the blood of donors, on which the tests used so far were based.
The nucleide acid tests made it possible to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period by less than one week.
We substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements led to a significant reduction in the risk of contracting AIDS by blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400 and 500 000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that you can now receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without concern, "says the head of the Héma-Québec management.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, as an example of the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant, "says Dr. Décary before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
"The needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need a red blood cell or platelet injection.
The ageing population also has consequences on the network of blood donors that regroup on average only 3% of Chequequese eligible for blood donation. "
All persons with good health, aged 18 and meeting the eligibility criteria, however, can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travelled in a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it's hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to hold them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since today's life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating his blood, "Francine Décary is grieved.
With a budget of $297 million per year, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that are almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was previously considered as biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We have celebrated a few weeks ago, the putting on the bank of our very thousand blood sample of the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year, "says Dr. Décary, who describes this cordon blood-taking program as very popular.
"Many moms are disappointed that they are not able to enjoy this," as Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all the hospitals in Quebec.
