Free opinion - The Orwellian Speech of Barrick Gold
In his September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world's largest gold company attempted a €6 million defamation process against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate."
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation persecutions, but the law.
Without surprise, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The result of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and the editor of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable amounts in order to prepare their defence and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the almost unfunded pockets of the mining company.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will chew the opposition as well as scare whoever will dare to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by hitting a stick.
It was therefore sufficient for the mining company to open its books, records and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that would have been able to clarify the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects the requests and support letters for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a "public" debate by disregarding the views of the public?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word only refers to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What you don't understand - or what you don't want to understand - Barrick Gold, is that the public that supports the authors and the editors of Noir Canada does it mainly because it rejects the brutal way of the mining.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and to judge him, but based on civilized changes of arguments, and not in the framework of what many people perceive as a persecution-gag (following the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just placed a requirement with respect to the authors of Noir Canada, urging them not to use this word any more).
In addition to Mr. Garver's surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on freedom of university search and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to hold a debate on facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under the punishment of many persecutions, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so in accordance with the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's unmeasured persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he does not want to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss to the university world, but also to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
