What did they produce at the Zuschlag & amp; Co. invoice factory?
The criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will soon begin on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing significant damage fraud, in a business way, continuously and in organized form in addition to other crimes, including falsification of documents.
According to the Office of the Prosecutor, the funds obtained in public competitive examinations were used for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the municipalities - in full about 65 million HUF - stopped in part in the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal and in part in the pocket of individuals.
The method, which was also made known by the researchers, was to justify the collection of the funds obtained in the public competitive examinations with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the various associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were false.
For this purpose they obtained the stoneware in the market of the Józsefváros District and the circular stamps were made in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that in the name of which company the counterfeit invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and they served as a model to make the invoices that he presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as the City Council of the Capital.
These invoices were signed for the most part by István Lados and his accomplice András Łri, who, according to our information, wrote the reports necessary to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However - according to the manager of the center - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the bill issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
As a hostel in the town of Badassonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however on the bill there were a hundred and thirty people.
But the great fantasy invoice manufacturers also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft. gastronomic center because in the holding of books of it - according to the information given to the Public Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
Győző Farkas, the manager of that company, informed hvg.hu that when he was summoned by the prosecution and showed him the bills, he knew that they were false documents.
"In the seal the name of our company and the NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal problems, he also did not agree that according to the bill a hundred people were accommodated, since they have only eleven rooms in which not so many people fit.
In addition, the bill also included meals, while the restaurant has not worked for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice manufacturers also did not report that the chosen travel agency in Budapest exclusively organizes travel abroad, so that on the cash bill they foolishly indicated a trip within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the agency's bill-issuing practice.
In addition, as was known during the investigation, VAT was also included in the document, despite the fact that travel outside the territory of the European Union was tax-free.
Among other things the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jövőért foundation, since the services of that company are not charged with 25 but only 15% of VAT, in addition the hotel employees only extended machine-made invoices however the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "consignors" made other mistakes as well, as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as an activity carried out the road transport to which - it has been known during the investigations of the prosecution - does not make the company founded as an investment consultant.
Also due to formal differences - inadequate invoice format, false seal - it was known that the invoices issued for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont are false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued these invoices.
The forgers also paid no attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, that is why the one in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
They consciously issued the invoices.
Another group of the manufacturers of false invoices are made up of those who were aware that they should issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Buduestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifju Szocialisták, issued an invoice worth about four million HUF on behalf of the Együtt Foundation to Harmadik Évezredért.
The manager of the Collab Kft. - according to the prosecution - was convinced by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi, to issue fictitious invoices.
He also collaborated with Zuschlag and his accomplices the Biogate Kft., currently under liquidation process, which in 2003 provided invoices of approximately 5 million HUF to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the Vörösfeyő Egyesület Association, without real economic activity behind.
There was no movement of capital either, as they later overturned the prepared invoices but forgot to record this entity in their documents.
The next group of fake invoice manufacturers include those that have some connection with the accused.
For example, Ivan Kubatov was the defendant of the Ukrainian manager of the Trio SL Delta with a fictional headquarters in Budapest, who dealt with the trade in fuels and vehicles.
The company issued numerous invoices worth approximately HUF 18 million in October, November and December 2005 on the sale of computer media.
According to the investigation data, these invoices were purchased by the Kft. Cash Investment in Kiskunhalas, which has been under liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The manager of this company was a Romanian to whom Ivan Kubatov should have also issued the documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We have information that Kubatov recognized during the investigation that he issued in the name of the company invoices for the Atlasz, for the Hoppá and for Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány by charging the amount himself.
The Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and the Jos-Investment Bt. were founded by Romanian masons at the express request of Ivan Kubatov.
However, none of the companies actually worked because, according to the defendant, they did not receive a job.
But he took advantage of these companies, as at the request of his accomplice, lawyer Zsolt Szente, who prepared the company's registration documents, issued invoices on behalf of the companies for the Zuschlag-related organizations: for the Atlasz and for the Y-Generácio.
Kubatov on behalf of the Cash Investment, the Delta Trió, the Fa-Bani Jos, the Jos Investment and the Linaxtrade gave a total of 15 invoices to different entities worth 14.2 million HUF.
The Office of the Prosecutor considered that Kubatov received VAT and 10 per cent of the amount of the invoices.
This man even took advantage of the Szi-Beri partnership to issue fictitious invoices used in the Biztos Pont competition.
The Y-Generácio and Szövetség to Modern Magyarországért presented a competition in January 2006 to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA), a public utility entity of the Socialist Party.
