On the other hand, netizens who care about people's rights, in May, were relieved when the company, together with the EFF, an electronic rights organization, successfully demonstrated in court that he was right in his dispute with the FBI: according to the sentence, Google cannot be forced, by any of the points of the constitution, to supply any information requested in secret by the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to obtain under the pretext of strengthening the child protection law passed years ago, about 50,000 web addresses and some thousand wanted phrases, but without obtaining the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of web pages and key words of the last two months.)
Thus, the opinion about Google is rather contradictory: it is criticized by those who fear to supply their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is damaged by the start of using Google services, and they rebel against it as against multinational conservative image companies.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, netizens and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "cutting-edge corporation," not its rival, the Microsoft, listed by its Windows as the conqueror of the World, however much they both fight for the same goal.
