The smart car imitates the flight of the beehive
What would be the best method for developing technologies to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of the existing nature obstacle sensors?
For example, the one with the beehives.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the beehives gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of the collision prevention system.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C-type robotic car management system imitator of nature, which was given the characteristics of the beehives, with the ultimate aim of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bee creates its own particular oval space that actually resembles our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technology director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of the beehives that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser-ray length measurement system.
It identifies the obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that is immediately transformed into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumps, changes the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system currently, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bee does to dodge other bee.
This process should be done in an eye-opening and closing.
However, unlike the bumps, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonal, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the beehives to dodge other beehives, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotating movement and the acceleration also the fragation.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, meaning that they have a longer life span than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, much less the storage capacity.
This device in each second should only process some input signals and react to the case.
It is not necessary to store these data or to react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so use only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
No memories of gigabytes, or megabytes are needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid the obstacles, which according to the Nissan's calculations, within ten years you can join the models made in series.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to bring the driver to its destination, avoiding the obstacles in its way.
