The written version of the $700 billion financial rescue package law has been prepared and will be applied in several phases in order to buy bad bank credits.
In the first phase, half the money will be spent.
According to the time of the eastern coast during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight Saturday, the congressional leaders reached an agreement on the $700 billion financial rescue package in total, after several days of discussion - the Reuters reported.
"We have made important progress," said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the American Congress, saying that the agreement needs to be formalized only in a document.
The commitment made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the commitment, said: this program will work and will be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving the Wall Street, but about turning the car of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets, that is, on Sunday before 8: 00 p.m., according to Washington's schedule (that is, before 2: 00 a.m. Monday morning, according to Central European schedule), without causing a spectacular leap in the bags.
On the bill called the emergency law for economic stabilization in 2008, the first Monday will vote for the American Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the agreement.
We are pleased with the progress made during the night and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all the $700 billion to buy low-quality credit fund securities.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, from this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy credit fund securities, bad rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion will be spent after a new Congress decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and credit fund securities, as well as other "poisonous" claims.
The purchase may be made in auctions or directly - the competent persons of the ministry have reported.
The law allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson said: the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can even reach 700 billion dollars to meet the urgent needs of the US financial system, be it the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could lead to the collapse of some large financial institutions.
We do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks that are in trouble and are waiting for the help of the State will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the American argot simply calls parachutes of gold.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, in addition to the limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the failed head of the bank is retired.
By directly buying bad credits the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the compensation of the bosses is not exaggerated.
In addition to the above, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations only concern new contracts to encourage participation in the programme as well.
This is the first case in American history that a legal limitation on the income of the directors-general will be in force - said Democrat Barney Frank, president of the Congress commission, responsible for the financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares from the banks participating in the programme, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, as they will ultimately even be able to make profits with the transaction as soon as the economy is recovered and with it the bank.
According to the bill over the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to return the financial sector losses to taxpayers.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed their reservations about the project.
"This is not what the American citizens entrusted us, that is, the taxpayers' dollars are not being protected," said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
His Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur said: the measures urged him by the same ones who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to last month's prices and 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007's prices - the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent over July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent over the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent over the previous month and 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices increased only to a minimum, with 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased at a minimum of 0.1 per cent over the month of July.
The largest increase in the size of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), due first to the 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 per cent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 per cent) in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing did not change.
In the other sectors of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first of all as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first July.
In a 12-month comparison - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, drink and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
During the past year in the global processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 per cent.
The prices of electricity, the supply of gas, heat and water exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate sector prices there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared with the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production branches, there was a decrease of 6.8 per cent and in investment goods by 1.4 per cent.
The industry's export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent over the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The contribution of our national currency in one month was reduced by 1.7 per cent over the euro and by 7.1 per cent over the dollar, compared to August 2007, it was strengthened by 7.5 per cent over the euro and 15.9 per cent over the dollar.
