Járóka: We must break the vicious circle of poverty and segregation
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has been launched in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also the President of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, a member of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that hit Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevaliation of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European social rights protection organisations.
Járóka - according to the press bureau of the Fidesz Group of Members of the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies are left out of the labour market in the first place because of their low level of schooling.
"Most young Roma have not completed secondary education and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can obtain a university diploma."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role to play in the prevention of other human rights as well.
Investment in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these issues both among Gypsies and among non-Gypsies.
For the sooner a gypsy student starts school, the more likely he will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the European Parliament, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary in order to immediately accelerate the processes of school re-education, for this it is of fundamental importance that the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives be properly implemented.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, Roma children must be given the possibility to guarantee the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens" - Járóka demanded.
The objective of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, organized annually since the Berlin meeting last year in the sign of the "European Year for Equal Opportunities," is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
