Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic rooms
The historical cinematographic rooms close by favoring the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas in a blind city, it's like a face without eyes."
The image offered by director Giuseppe Tornatore photographer with effective what is happening in the large Italian urban centres and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalizing the cinemas, which with the birth of the large metichs on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono-rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory, "it is as if a friend, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place was shared and so much emotion," notes the director of the new Paradiso cinema, the film that was won 20 years ago by cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury to Cannes, which counted the poetry of a provincial film room and the nostalgia for the way to live the cinema that he lost perhaps forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of the merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay for the most part are all the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are as first, Emilia-Romaña with 82 cinemas less, following Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the one responsible for its disappearance is the compromise of the multiplex, these three Italian regions are own that have recorded the largest number of new meticon cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardia in the last five years, 81 be in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romaña.
"The Italian exercise has developed irrationally," says Paolo Protti, President of the Anec, "it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to ensure the permanence of those already existing, because when a city room closes, not all its frequents are willing to transfer to the metichs.
Not to mention the lack of funds for traders: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year. "
The case of Bologna, the first Italian city to be concerned about the closures, decided to repair with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono sala be in the historical center that at the periphery.
The proposed rules include tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: viewers can enter the limited traffic area and will have special parking rates.
"It is an initiative that I like," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope other cities will follow the Bologna example by setting up other measures.
It is true that to contrast the extra power of the metichs, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of the sound and the image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is an issue that was always important to me: the closure of the Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to perform the "New Paradiso cinema," which I had thought for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale of the already closed Nazionale way, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so that I do not see the signs blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side. "
