When the energy is born from the waves, the great ones come down to the stage
It is an exterminated field that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and is now discovering it, the great world energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the big ones look like Chevron.
The possibility of raising energy from the movements of the sea has been under consideration for a hundred years and in the 1970s, together with the first oil crisis, investigations intensified.
When the price of oil was low, in 1980, the idea of taking advantage of marine energy was removed, but now that environmental cases and the new increase in oil give the sector a boost.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated for 2007 that 15 percent of the world's power need could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of the waves of the sea.
This would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would also be the currents and the tides.
Giants to the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in North Portugal.
When the intention was announced, it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away from betting on marine energy, it is always more and among these companies that have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying the technology on ocean energy - he has declared the spokesman of a company associated with the ha to the American oil colossus to the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal - and is assessing the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the US energy commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a rather important signal, if it is considered that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan to perform new drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of the energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed, indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts talk about a technology still at the beginning, because marine energy has no doubt that it has a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts such as those of Portuguese or Scottish are small and do not seem to create great problems for the ecosystem.
To produce long-scale energy, a technology with greater environmental impact should be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a boas system united between them.
The force of the waves, which makes the boas move up and down, becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure rotates a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast through submarine cables.
For now there are four implants of this type under development, waiting only for federal approval, aside from energy, could serve a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping center and a parking lot, using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of the water when there are tides, turns the pallets of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said that he has a long cast of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say at the Institute for the Development of Electric Energy, deserves at this time the potential of tides.
While this is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is especially about tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others that approach the coast, have invested $7 and a half million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
